4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA DECLARING THAT THE FISCAL AND MONETARY POLICIES OF THE FEDERAL
6 GOVERNMENT ARE HARMING THE PEOPLE OF MONTANA AND THE UNITED STATES, AND URGING
7 CONGRESS TO DISCIPLINE ITSELF AND ADDRESS THE ONGOING DEFICITS AND DEBT OF THE
8 UNITED STATES BEFORE THERE IS NO LONGER ANY REMEDY TO AVOID HYPERINFLATION OR A
9 DEFAULT ON THE DEBT OF THIS COUNTRY.
10
11 WHEREAS, the federal debt of the United States has increased from $21.2 trillion in 2016 to $36.3
12 trillion as of 2025, equaling 121% of the nation's gross domestic product; and
13 WHEREAS, the federal debt of the United States is expected to exceed $55 trillion by 2034; and
14 WHEREAS, interest payments on federal debt have increased from $260 billion in 2016 to $1.1 trillion
15 in 2024, totaling 45% of federal income tax revenue and a 30% increase from 2023; and
16 WHEREAS, the national deficit for fiscal year 2024 was $1.8 trillion; and
17 WHEREAS, federal borrowing costs are expected to be $1.47 trillion for the first 6 months of fiscal year
18 2025 and $19.5 trillion over the next 10 years; and
19 WHEREAS, the United States debt service reached 3.95% of gross domestic product in fiscal year
20 2024, and gross domestic product growth is only projected at 1.8% for the next decade; and
21 WHEREAS, only four times in the past 48 years has Congress managed to pass a budget on time; and
22 WHEREAS, Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid are currently running annual deficits of $1.17
23 trillion a year; and
24 WHEREAS, the International Monetary Fund has warned the United States that increased government
25 spending, growing public debt, and loose fiscal policy are leading to elevated interest rates and sustained
26 inflation; and
27 WHEREAS, sustained inflation and interest rates have led to crippling price increases on essential
28 food, transportation, energy, and housing, harming Montanans and American consumers; and
